#. +> trunk5
#: ../../tutorials/krita-brush-tips/animated_brushes.rst:17
msgid "Animated brushes are officially called ‘image hoses’, and they're quite fun. They are basically :ref:`brush tips <predefined_brush_tip>` with multiple image files."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../tutorials/krita-brush-tips/animated_brushes.rst:19
msgid "The typical way to make them is to first draw the ‘frames’ on a small canvas, per layer:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../tutorials/krita-brush-tips/animated_brushes.rst:25
msgid "You can use the :kbd:`Alt +` |mouseleft| shortcut on the layer thumbnails to isolate layers without hiding them."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../tutorials/krita-brush-tips/animated_brushes.rst:30
msgid "When done you should have a mess like this."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../tutorials/krita-brush-tips/animated_brushes.rst:32
msgid "Go into the brush settings (:kbd:`F5` key), and go to predefined brush-tips, and click :guilabel:`stamp`. You will get this window."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../tutorials/krita-brush-tips/animated_brushes.rst:37
msgid "And then use style **animated** and selection mode set to **random**."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../tutorials/krita-brush-tips/animated_brushes.rst:39
msgid "Krita uses :ref:`Gimp’s image hose format <file_gih>` which allows for random selection of the images, angle based selection, pressure based selection, and incremental selection."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../tutorials/krita-brush-tips/animated_brushes.rst:41
msgid "When you create a brushtip, Krita will automatically switch to it for the current brush, but you will always be able to find it in the predefined brushes tab."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../tutorials/krita-brush-tips/animated_brushes.rst:46
msgid "And now you can use it to paint trees! (for example)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../tutorials/krita-brush-tips/animated_brushes.rst:48
msgid "You can also use animated brush tips to emulate :ref:`bristle brush tips <heightmap_bristle_brush_tips>` that go from very fine bristles to a fully opaque stamp based on pressure, like a dry paintbrush might do. Or make incremental patterns like the ones you see on porcelain."
msgstr ""

